abstract: Our reporters followed all of the exchanges and fact-checked the candidates, providing context and explanation on the policy debates.
snippet: Our reporters followed all of the exchanges and fact-checked the candidates, providing context and explanation on the policy debates.
lead_paragraph: Ten candidates vying for the 2020 Democratic presidential nomination took the stage Thursday night in Houston for the third round of debates. Unlike the previous debates, which took place over two evenings, only one night was needed to feature all who qualified for the showdown.

headline_main: Analysis of the Sept. 12 Democratic Debate

abstract: Joe Biden hugged Barack Obama tightly as the former vice president came under attack from Bernie Sanders and Julin Castro. Elizabeth Warren went unscathed, while Kamala Harris stuck to a script.
snippet: Joe Biden hugged Barack Obama tightly as the former vice president came under attack from Bernie Sanders and Julin Castro. Elizabeth Warren went unscathed, while Kamala Harris stuck to a script.
lead_paragraph: Thursdays Democratic primary debate was the first time all the leading candidates were onstage together. The most illuminating exchanges were not between Joseph R. Biden Jr. and Elizabeth Warren, who met onstage for the first time, but from other pairings. Here are six highlights from the debate.

abstract: Joe Biden, Kamala Harris, Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren are the leading Democrats in the presidential primary. We take a look back at their debate performances.
snippet: Joe Biden, Kamala Harris, Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren are the leading Democrats in the presidential primary. We take a look back at their debate performances.
lead_paragraph: HOUSTON  Ahead of Thursdays debate, we looked back at how the leading Democratic candidates  Joseph R. Biden Jr., Kamala Harris, Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren  performed in the first two debates.
